quran[11]{c,v,t,f}:
17,28,"(v) And when you must turn away from them - (that is, from the destitute, the near of kin, the needy, and the wayfarer) - in pursuit of God's Mercy which you expect to receive, then speak to them kindly. {1}",footnotes:1:These three articles are meant to impress that a man should not reserve his earnings and his wealth exclusively for his own person. He should do his utmost to fulfill his own necessities of life in a moderate way and render the rights of his relatives
17,29,"(vi) Do not keep your hand fastened to your neck nor outspread it, altogether outspread, for you will be left sitting rebuked, destitute. {1}",footnotes:1:“And do not keep your hand fastened to your neck”
17,30,"Certainly Your Lord makes plentiful the provision of whomsoever He wills and straitens it for whomsoever He wills. He is well-aware and is fully observant of all that relates to His servants. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
17,31,"(vii) Do not kill your children for fear of want. We will provide for them and for you. Surely killing them is a great sin. {1}",footnotes:1:This verse cuts at the very root of the movement of birth control
17,32,"(viii) Do not even approach fornication for it is an outrageous act, and an evil way. {1}",footnotes:1:“And do not come near to adultery”. This commandment is meant both for individuals and society as a whole. It warns each individual not only to guard against adultery or fornication itself but against all those things that lead to or stimulate it. As regards to society as a whole the commandment enjoins it to make such arrangements as prevent adultery and eradicate the means and stimulants that lead to adultery. Therefore
17,33,"(ix) Do not kill any person whom Allah has forbidden to kill, {1} except with right. {2} We have granted the heir of him who has been wrongfully killed the authority to {3} (claim retribution);so let him not exceed in slaying. {4} He shall be helped. {5}",footnotes:1:When the Islamic state was established
17,34,"(x) And do not even go near the property of the orphan - except that it be in the best manner - till he attains his maturity. {1} (xi) And fulfil the covenant, for you will be called to account regarding the covenant. {2}",footnotes:1:This too
17,35,"(xii) Give full measure when you measure, and weigh with even scales. {1} That is fair and better in consequence. {2}",footnotes:1:This instruction was not confined to individuals only but it has been made a part of the duties of an Islamic government to supervise transactions in the markets and streets to see that exact measures and weights are being observed
17,36,"(xiii) Do not follow that of which you have no knowledge. Surely the hearing, the sight, the heart - each of these shall be called to account. {1}",footnotes:1:The meanings of “Do not follow that of which you have no knowledge” are very comprehensive. It demands that both in individual and collective life
17,37,"(xiv) Do not strut about in the land arrogantly. Surely you cannot cleave the earth, nor reach the heights of the mountains in stature. {1}",footnotes:1:This instruction warns against the ways of tyrants and vain people and is not merely meant for the individual but also for the collective conduct of the Muslim community. It was because of this guidance that the rulers
17,38,"The wickedness of each of that is hateful to your Lord. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
